article.headline: Utah 51, Weber State 38
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Weber State stopped No. 19 Utah scorers
Kim Smith and Shona Thorburn. The Wildcats didn't count on Mandie
Little's performance.

Little had 15 points and 10 rebounds, and Kelsy Stireman added a
season-high 15 points and seven steals in No. 19 Utah's 51-38 win
Saturday over Weber State.

"They were really physical defensively right from the start and
that got me fired up to play hard," said Little, who made 6-of-11
shots and had five of her rebounds on the offensive end to lift the
Utes (7-3) to their 21st consecutive home victory.

Weber State focused on stopping Smith and Thorburn, the Utes'
leading scorers, and often left Utah's other players open.

"They were helping off of me so [Utah coach Elaine Elliott]
told me I needed to look for my shot and score a little more,"
said Stireman, who obliged with a variety of successful drives to
the basket.

Kristen Clyder-Gardner led Weber State (2-7) with nine points
and Erica McGuire had eight, but the Wildcats failed to take
advantage of Utah's offensive woes.

"The team really bought into our defensive game plan. We wanted
to make someone else shoot the ball so we were doubling Smith and
Thorburn," Weber State coach Carla Taylor said.

Smith, who played the entire game, made 2-of-11 shots and scored
a career-low five points. Thorburn had eight points and six
turnovers. But Little made up the difference.

"Mandie is the kid that will play great in a physical game like
that. She'll get nasty with you," Elliott said.

Utah (7-3), which often ranks at the top of the NCAA defensive
scoring rankings, allowed Oregon State to shoot a season-high 63
percent and upset the Utes 71-62 on Tuesday.

But the Ute defense returned to form against Weber State,
limiting the Wildcats to 33 percent shooting, forcing 21 turnovers,
and causing numerous off-balance attempts to beat the shot clock.

"After the Oregon State game, we have spent all of our time
working on defense. But our offense was certainly not flowing
today. Good thing we were able to stop them," Elliott said.

Utah led from start to finish and seemed in firm control after
Julie Wood's baseline jumper made it 39-26 midway through the
second half. But Julie Gjertsen scored five in a 9-0 run that
brought the Wildcats within four points.

Utah immediately responded with an 8-0 surge, capped by
Stireman's jumpshot with 3:07 remaining for a 47-35 lead. Utah's
defense held the Wildcats without a field goal for the rest of the
game.

"I thought our defense was great, especially at the end. It
made up for the offensive struggles we had," Little said.

Despite 13 turnovers and just one point by Smith, Utah led 22-17
at halftime after Lana Sitterud stole the ball and fed Thorburn for
a layup just before the buzzer.

The only other time Smith failed to score at least 10 points was
in a conference tournament loss to BYU last season.
